ise Marie Roth explores the process of giving birth, and the ways in which medicine and law interact to shape maternity care.Focusing on the United States, Roth explores how the law creates an environment where medical providers, malpractice attorneys, and others limit women’s rights and choices during birth. She shows how a fear of liability risk often drives the decision-making process of medical providers, who prioritize hospital efficiency over patient safety, to the detriment of mothers themselves.Ultimately, Roth advocates for an approach that protects the reproductive rights of mothers. A comprehensive overview, The Business of Birth provides valuable insight into the impact of the law on mothers, medical providers, maternity care practices, and others in the United States.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aMaternal health servicesxEconomic aspectszUnited States. 0aMaternal health serviceszUnited States. 0aObstetriciansxMalpracticezUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Marriage & Family.2bisacsh  aAuthoritative knowledge.  aBirth.  aCesarean.  aChoice.  aCourt-ordered cesareans.  aDefensive medicine.  aDisrespectful care/Obstetric violence.  aEarly-term birth.  aElective delivery.  aElectronic fetal monitor.  aEvidence-based medicine.  aFeticide.  aForced cesareans.  aHealthcare system.  aInduction of labor.  aInstitutional culture.  aLegal endogeneity.  aLegal regimes.  aLiability insurance.  aMalpractice.  aMaternity care field.  aMaternity care.  aMedical malpractice.  aMedical professional dominance.  aMedicalization of childbirth.  aMidwife-attended birth.  aMidwifery model.  aMidwifery.  aOrganizational efficiency.  aOut-of-hospital birth.  aPrenatal substance abuse.  aReproductive Justice.  aReproductive regimes.  aReprod